On behalf of the AMERICAN INDIAN HERITAGE DAY in Texas, we extend our prayers and condolences to the Alabama-Coushatta Tribe of Texas in the passing of their Mikko Choba Skalaaba - Principal Chief, Herbert G. Johnson, Sr. In the early years, the Alabama-Coushatta used to bring their basketball teams (women and men) to participate in Dallas tournaments and would walk away with first-place trophies. Herb Johnson usually received the MVP or All-Star recognitions, said Peggy Larney. A member of the Beaver Clan, Mr. Johnson served his people in many capacities throughout his entire life. He was twice elected to the Tribal Council and worked as the Tribal Security Director for over twenty-one years. He was elected as the Tribe’s Second Chief on October 5, 2013, and remained in that position until he was installed as Principal Chief following the passing of the then Principal Chief – Mikko Colabe III – the late Clem Sylestine in 2019. A deacon and elder at the Indian Presbyterian Church, Mr. Johnson also served on the Big Sandy (Dallardsville) School Board for 48 years. Herbert G. Johnson, Sr. was born on April 3, 1942, on the Alabama-Coushatta Tribe of Texas Indian Reservation near Livingston, Texas. After high school, Mr. Johnson enrolled at Jacksonville College in Jacksonville, Texas. A Jacksonville College legend, he earned All-American status in Basketball following the 1963 season. Although he stood only 5’6”, he set a then all-time national record when he scored 67 points in a single game. He went on to average 33.5 points a game for the season in an era that did not feature a 3-point shot. Jacksonville College honored Mr. Johnson as a Distinguished Alumnus in 2020. Mr. Johnson also attended the University of Houston and played for Coach Guy V. Lewis for one year. When asked by the Smithsonian National Museum of American Indians what message he would like to share with Tribal youth, Mr. Johnson stated, “Our future lies with you. Choose a good path, follow it, and fulfill your dreams. Keep your traditions alive. Make good choices. Always stay positive and make a difference.”    Herb Johnson Patrick Battise Heather Johnson Battise Retha Johnson  Camille N. Johnson  Kyle Eagle Williams Davie Johnson Alabama Coushatta Tribe of Texas Alabama Coushatta Tribe Epa Alabama-Coushatta Tribe Daycare Alabama Coushatta Tribe of Texas Alabama-Coushatta Pow-wow I travelled back to US successfully after staying in Doha for 14 days. The entry rules to Qatar has changed from Aug 2nd and fully vaccinated tourists have to quarantine for 10 days in a hotel booked thru discover Qatar. I don’t have more information on that it’s best to check Qatar public health website for latest rules. Here’s my experience on my Doha - US leg. You’ll need to get covid test 72 hrs before your flight. I got mine done at Aster Hospital at Al Salah St. They charge 250 QAR and take walk-ins. They are very responsive over WhatsApp and very helpful. I got my results back within 24hrs. Make sure the report has a QR code and verify your details in the report. My flight was on Aug 2nd at 1.10am. I reached the airport at 9pm on aug 1st (paranoid n wanted to reach airport early). They opened the check in counter only at 10.30pm. They do a pre-check where they verify your passport, ticket, US visa and RTPCR report. They also checked my Doha immigrant stamp to verify if I stayed in Doha for 14 days before traveling to US. At the check in counter they verified all the documents again, asked me to sign a CDC declaration form. After all the verification I was given boarding pass. Immigration at Doha was simple, no questions asked. After that you go to security check. My flight was full so there was a long queue to enter the gate area. This took us more than 30 min. They’ll again verify your passport, visa and boarding pass. One more security check here and then you’re good to board the flight. My POE was Chicago. They ask you to fill in the immigration form, one per family. Immigration was straight forward. They asked where we came from, our purpose of travel and where we worked. Hope this helps. Feel free to reach out to me if you have any questions उठे रोमांरोमातून!! दिनांक आठ ॲागस्ट! पुन्हा एक परेड! वेगळं उपनगर! परेडला सुरूवात होण्याआधी लहान मुलांचा लेझीमचा कार्यक्रम! माऊली , माऊली ह्या गाण्यावर नाच करणारी ती छोटुकली आणि त्यांचे शिक्षक ह्यांनी कार्यक्रमाला बहार आणली! तर आजची परेड मायभूमीसाठी! परेडला खूपशा भारतीयांचे फ्लोट्स! त्यातच एक आपला, महाराष्ट मंडळ शिकागोचा शेवटच्या नंबरचा फ्लोट! फ्लोटवर कुठेही अवास्तव सजावट नाही, भपका नाही, होता तो फक्त दिमाखात वावरणारा बॅनर! तेव्हढीच सजावट! आणि तेव्हढीच पुरेशी कारण खरी सजावट तर व्हायची होती! हळूहळू परेडसाठीच्या पार्किंग लॅाटमध्ये गर्दी वाढायला लागली. सगळे फ्लोट्स तयार झाले. आपली मंडळीसुद्धा हजेरी लावायला लागली. इकडून तिकडे लगबग सुरू! एकमेकांना बोलावणारे आवाज, गडबड आणि बरंच काही! तेव्हढ्यात एका गाडीतून पालखी बाहेर काढली गेली कारण आजची थीम होती वारी आणि ग्रंथदिंडी! ही पालखी उचलून ठेवतानाचा भक्तीभाव आपसूकच सगळ्यांच्या चेहऱ्यावर दिसायला लागला. तेव्हढ्यात चारपाच गॅाल्फकार्टमधून ढोल, ताशे घेऊन इतर मंडळींचं आगमन झालं. वातावरण आणखीनच लगबगीचं होऊन गेलं. मंडळी ढोलताशे घेऊन फ्लोटवर सज्ज! आणि हीच होती फ्लोटची खरी सजावट!! सगळ्यात पुढे दोन्ही देशांचे झेंडे घेऊन काही मंडळी तय्यार! एका ट्रकमध्ये स्पीकर्स वाजायला लागले आणि वातावरण विठ्ठलमय होऊन गेलं. ‘तुला साद आली तुझ्या लेकरांची’ असं म्हणताक्षणी ह्या लेकरांचे पाय लयीत, टाळ, लेझीम घेऊन पदन्यास करायला लागले. चेहऱ्यावरून भक्तिभाव ओसंडून वाहत होता आणि शरीरात एक वेगळ्याच प्रकारची ऊर्जा होती. इकडे ह्या वारकऱ्यांचा पदन्यास सुरू झाला आणि तिकडे ढोलताशावर दणक्यात थाप पडली. आता वातावरण निर्मिती झाली नाही तरच नवल होतं. हळूहळू मंडळी पुढे सरकायला लागली. पुढे झेंडे, त्यामागे माऊलींना आळवणारा आवाज, ट्रकच्यामागे नामरूपात तल्लीन झालेले वारकरी, डोक्यावर तुळशीवृंदावन घेऊन चालणाऱ्या भाविक महिला,वारकऱ्यांच्यामागे पालखी उचलून चालणारे चार वारकरी आणि सगळ्यात मागे ढोलताशाचे निनाद!! परेड पुढे जात होती , अंतर कापलं जात होतं पण जसा जसा विठ्ठलाचा गजर वाढत चालला होता तशीतशी विठ्ठलाशी जवळीक साधली जात होती. रणरणतं ऊन, घाम गाळणारं तापमान पण चेहऱ्यावर होतं ते समाधान आणि बरोबर होते ते सातत्याने पदन्यास करणारे पाय!! परेड बघणाऱ्यांची गर्दी काही भागांत थोडी कमी तर काही भागांत जास्त! गर्दी कमी म्हणून कुठेही पदन्यासात किंवा ढोलताशांवर पडणाऱ्या थापेत हयगय नाही पण जिथे गर्दी जास्त तिथे डबल उत्साह! एव्हाना परेड अंतिम टप्प्यात आली आणि ह्या वारकऱ्यांच्या उत्साहाला उधाणच आलं. ह्या दुतर्फा गर्दीच्या रस्त्यावर परेडचा शेवट करताकरता पुन्हा एकदा उत्साहाची सळसळ! पुन्हा एकदा टाळ, लेझीम, ढोल, ताशा ह्यांचा भावपूर्ण नाद! आणि त्यात भर पडली गरागरा फुगड्या घालणाऱ्या भाविकांची ( अगदी प्रेक्षकांमधल्या भाविकांचीपण)! विठ्ठलाचा नामजप मनात आणि हृदयातसुद्धा!! एव्हाना अशी अवस्था झाली होती की, अवघे गरजे नेपरव्हिल, जाहला नामाचा गजर!! पण आता ह्या परेडचा शेवट करणं भाग होतं, विठ्ठलाचा गजर करत पालखी खाली ठेवली गेली पण पालखी उचलतानाचाच उत्साह आणि भक्तिभाव, पालखी खाली ठेवतानाही कायम! घामाने थबथबलेले चेहरे आणि विठ्ठलनामात रममाण झालेली मनं ह्याचा सुरेख संगम इथे दिसत होता. एकूणच ही परेड, ही दिंडी, ही वारी मंत्रमुग्ध करून सोडणारी आणि कधीही संपू नये असं वाटणारीच होती. आम्ही एकमेकांचे निरोप घ्यायला सुरूवात केली. वरवर औपचारिक निरोप पण मनात ,झालेल्या वारीची उजळणी आणि हृदयाच्या प्रत्येक ठोक्याबरोबर ऐकू येणारा विठ्ठलाचा गजर! हे ह्या वारीचंच श्रेय आहे, नाही का? परेड संपली आणि एकदम विजांचा कडकडाट झाला, पावसाची लक्षणं दिसायला लागली. बहुधा ती वीज ,नामाचा गजर संपला म्हणून नाराज झाली असावी आणि आकाशानेपण त्याच कारणाकरता थोडे अश्रू ढाळले असावेत, नाही का? तर अशी ही भारावून टाकणारी परेड! ह्यासाठी कष्ट घेतलेल्या किती भक्तांची नावं सांगू? त्यासाठी लागणारं प्लॅनिंग, गरजेच्या असलेल्या आणि वेळात वेळ काढून केलेल्या प्रॅक्टिसेस! किती किती आणि काय काय सांगू? पण ह्या सगळ्यांच्या कष्टामागे भक्तिभाव होता आणि त्यांच्यावर विठ्ठलाचा वरदहस्त! मग काय सोने पे सुहागाच!! एकंदरच हा अनुभव प्रत्यक्ष घेणाऱ्याला प्रत्येकाला आज एक वेगळंच समाधान मिळालं असणार ह्यात काहीच शंका नाही. किंबहुना हे समाधान नकळतच त्यांच्या मनात आणि चेहऱ्यावर रेंगाळलं तर त्यात नवल वाटायचं काहीच कारण नाही कारण विठ्ठलनाम हे भारावून टाकणारच आहे ह्यात काही शंकाच नाही! मला अजूनही माझ्या ह्रदयाच्या प्रत्येक ठोक्यात फक्त आणि फक्त ऐकू येतंय, ‘ विठ्ठल ,विठ्ठल ,विठ्ठल ,विठ्ठल’ !!! विठ्ठल, विठ्ठल , विठ्ठल , The 2018 Asian Games and the 2018 Commonwealth Games saw his 88.06m gold medal winning record in men’s javelin. He had also brought home a gold medal from the 2017 Asian Athletic Championships. A farmer’s son, Neeraj was conferred with the Arjuna Award when he was only 19 in 2018. Since 2016, he has been serving in the Indian Army. His historic achievement took India’s medal count to 7 this Olympics season.\n\nIt won’t be extravagant to say that this gem of India has a Midas touch.","message":"Finally, India brought gold home from the Tokyo Olympics. 22-year-old Subedar Neeraj Chopra from Haryana became the first Indian to win an individual gold medal in the Tokyo Olympics 2020 by hurling the javelin at 88.07m that broke his own previous records. The 2018 Asian Games and the 2018 Commonwealth Games saw his 88.06m gold medal winning record in men’s javelin. He had also brought home a gold medal from the 2017 Asian Athletic Championships. A farmer’s son, Neeraj was conferred with the Arjuna Award when he was only 19 in 2018. Since 2016, he has been serving in the Indian Army. Even with the bloody carnage of the Civil War, the brutal atrocities at Sand Creek shocked the nation.\nDuring hearings in Denver, Captain Soule’s integrity and unwavering testimony turned the tide against the once popular Chivington and the other men who participated in the massacre and mutilations at Sand Creek. Captain Soule fully realized that telling the truth about the massacre could cost him his life, even telling a good friend that he fully expected to be killed for his testimony.\nHe was right. Walking home with his new bride a short time later, Silas Soule was ambushed and shot in the head by an assassin who had participated in the Sand Creek Massacre. Silas Soule’s funeral, held just a few weeks after his wedding, was one of the most attended in Denver up until that time.\nWhile Captain Silas Soule’s name has largely faded into history, he stands out as one of the few bright rays of light in the moral darkness that surrounds the Sand Creek Massacre.\nHe should be remembered.”\nArtwork title ~ \"Captain Silas S, Soule, A Man With A Good Heart\".\nArtist, George C. Levi, Southern Cheyenne. Mixed media, antique ledger sheet, 7 ½ x 12 ½. - George C. Levi is a member of the Southern Cheyenne Tribe of Oklahoma. 19:55:01","updated":"2022-01-06 20:18:47","type":"photo","message":"Committing Genocide against American Indians by Law again. American Indian History and the Indian Removal Act are being erased from the Texas social studies curriculum. American Indian Heritage Day in Texas and Indian Citizens Against Racial Exploitation are collaborating with Dallas Truth, Racial Healing & Transformation to carry the cultural preservation of American Indian history at the American Indian Heritage Day in Texas Celebration. We will start conversations toward making key points to have our identity not erased again in Texas history. � We want to extend our invitation to all students, teachers, and school administration. This event is FREE! On Chickasaw Land . . . . . . . . . . Bill: SB 3 Texas Legislature advanced a bill that would reshape how social studies teachers can discuss race and current events in their classrooms. We wanted to bring awareness of Texas State Bill No. 3. As our American Indian identity has been erased from being taught in the Texas school systems. Senate Bill 3, which passed last Friday 18 votes to 4, will eliminate most mentions of people of color from the state’s required curriculum. More than two dozen curriculum requirements have been cut by the bill.�� Senate Bill 3 features more changes than two House bills that have been filed for the special legislative session that began Thursday. The legislation comes after Gov. Greg Abbott signed into law a bill from this year’s regular legislative session that restricts how current events and America’s history of racism can be taught in Texas schools. It’s been commonly referred to as the “critical race theory” bill, though the term “critical race theory” never appears in it. In signing it, Abbott said “more must be done” to “abolish critical race theory in Texas” and later put the issue on the special session agenda. Teachers and experts say that critical race theory, an academic framework used to examine structural causes of racial inequity, is not being taught in K-12 schools — and that the phrase is being used as a catch-all for any mention of racism, which is an integral part of teaching history truthfully. Critical race theory itself critiques the focus on individual blame in contemporary discussions of racism and shifts the focus to legal and social systems that perpetuate inequity. The law that already passed lists documents, figures, and events that must be included in the social studies curriculum. But SB 3, filed by state Sen. Bryan Hughes on Friday, strips out most mentions of women and people of color in that section — more than two dozen requirements that include Native American history, work by civil rights activists Cesar Chavez and Dolores Huerta, historical documents related to the Chicano movement and women’s suffrage, and writings by Martin Luther King Jr., Susan B. Anthony and Frederick Douglass. It also removes the requirement to teach “the history of white supremacy, including but not limited to the institution of slavery, the eugenics movement, and the Ku Klux Klan, and the ways in which it is morally wrong. ”��BY ISABELLA ZOU�Texas Tribune� . . . . . . . . . . . . 12:58:12","updated":"2022-01-06 20:18:47","type":"photo","message":"Committing Genocide against American Indians by Law again. American Indian History and the Indian Removal Act are being erased from the Texas social studies curriculum. American Indian Heritage Day in Texas and Indian Citizens Against Racial Exploitation are collaborating with Dallas Truth, Racial Healing & Transformation to carry the cultural preservation of American Indian history at the American Indian Heritage Day in Texas Celebration. We will start conversations toward making key points to have our identity not erased again in Texas history. We want to extend our invitation to all students, teachers, and school administration. This event is FREE! #OnChickasawLand . . . . . . . . . . HB 3979 During the regular legislative session that ended in May, Republicans rallied to pass House Bill 3979, which limits how teachers can discuss race and current events in social studies courses and bars them from awarding students course credit for social or political advocacy work. It’s the latest GOP push to restrict the teaching of critical race theory, a framework used to examine racism in colleges and universities that has become a Republican catch-all term for what some see as divisive efforts to address racism and inequity in schools. The Senate gave final approval to Senate Bill 3, a broad measure expanding HB 3979’s restrictions to any subject in grades K-12, including ethnic studies courses. It was passed on an 18-4 vote, with nine Democrats absent while in Washington, D.C., to join House Democrats in a protest over GOP voting bills. The House, however, cannot accept SB 3 due to a lack of quorum in the lower chamber. USA Today María Méndez Austin American-Statesman . . . . . . . . . . Bill: HB 3979 Legislative Session: 87(R) Last Action: 06/15/2021 E Effective on 9/1/21 Caption Version: Enrolled Caption Text: Relating to the social studies curriculum in public schools.
